<theorem xmlns="Theorem"
         xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance"
         type="Corollary"
         id="Thm_QuotientContinuous"
         xsi:schemaLocation="Theorem file:/C:/xampp/htdocs/moodle/mod/msm/NewSchemas/Theorem.xsd">
   <caption>Quotient of continuous maps</caption>
   <statement.theorem>
      <para>
         <para.body>Let <math>
               <latex>f,g\from D\to \RNr</latex>
            </math> be functions, and let <math>
               <latex>Z:=\Set{ t\in \RNr\st g(t) = 0}</latex>
            </math>. If <math>
               <latex>f</latex>
            </math> and <math>
               <latex>g</latex>
            </math> are continuous at <math>
               <latex>x\in \StDffrnc{ D }{ Z}</latex>
            </math>, then the quotient function</para.body>
      </para>
      <math.display>
         <latex>(f/g)\from (\StDffrnc{D}{Z}) \longrightarrow \RNr,\quad (f/g)(t):=\dfrac{f(t)}{g(t)}</latex>
      </math.display>
      <para>
         <para.body>is continuous at <math>
               <latex>x</latex>
            </math>.</para.body>
      </para>
   </statement.theorem>
   <proof>
      <proof.block>
         <proof.block.body>
            <para>
               <para.body>Using the inverse function <math>
                     <latex>p\from (\StDffrnc{\RNr}{0})\to (\StDffrnc{ \RNr }{ 0 })</latex>
                  </math>, we express the function <math>
                     <latex>(f/g)</latex>
                  </math> as a composite of functions as follows:</para.body>
            </para>
            <ol>
               <li>
                  <para>
                     <para.body>
                        <math>
                           <latex>(1/g) = p\Comp g</latex>
                        </math>, which is continuous at <math>
                           <latex>x</latex>
                        </math>, as <math>
                           <latex>g</latex>
                        </math> is continuous at <math>
                           <latex>x</latex>
                        </math> and <math>
                           <latex>p</latex>
                        </math> is continuous at <math>
                           <latex>g(x)</latex>
                        </math>.</para.body>
                  </para>
               </li>
               <li>
                  <para>
                     <para.body>Thus <math>
                           <latex>f\cdot (1/g)</latex>
                        </math> is continuous at <math>
                           <latex>x</latex>
                        </math>, as both functions <math>
                           <latex>f</latex>
                        </math> and <math>
                           <latex>(1/g)</latex>
                        </math> are continuous at <math>
                           <latex>x</latex>
                        </math>.</para.body>
                  </para>
               </li>
            </ol>
            <para>
               <para.body>This was to be shown.</para.body>
            </para>
         </proof.block.body>
      </proof.block>
   </proof>
</theorem>
